<http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-9968297/R-HSA-9968297>
        a       <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0016446> , <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#NamedIndividual> ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment>
                "Germinal center B cells possess a unique, error-prone base excision repair pathway that generates about 35% of mutations at A and T residues and most of the transversions at G and C residues in variable regions of immunoglobulin genes during somatic hypermutation (IJspeert et al. 2019, reviewed in Pilzecker and Jacobs 2019, Stratigopoulou et al. 2020). Mismatch repair initiated by MSH2:MSH6 is responsible for the remaining 65% of mutations at A and T residues (IJspeert et al. 2019).<br>UNG2, the nuclear isoform of uracil-DNA glycosylase (UNG) hydrolyzes the glycosidic bond in deoxyuridine in DNA to release uracil and produce an abasic site. In somatic hypermutation, the abasic site is recognized by APEX2 rather than the usual APEX1 (inferred from mouse homologs in Stavnezer et al. 2014, Schrader et al. 2023). APEX2 interacts with PCNA (Tsuchimoto et al. 2001, Burkovics et al. 2009) and endonucleolytically cleaves a single strand of double-stranded DNA adjacent to the abasic site created by UNG2 (Hadi and Wilson 2000, Hadi et al. 2002, Burkovics et al. 2006). APEX2 then excises 10-12 nucleotides to create a single stranded gap (Hadi and Wilson 2000, Hadi et al. 2002, Burkovics et al. 2006). Ubiquitinated PCNA recruits error-prone DNA polymerases POLH (Plosky et al. 2006), POLI (Haracska et al. 2001, 2005, Vidal et al. 2004, Cui et al. 2010), and POLZ (inferred from yeast homologs in Makarova et al. 2012) and the deoxycytidyl transferase REV1 (inferred from yeast homologs in Garg and Burgers 2005) to fill the gap, thereby creating mutations at or near the abasic site. REV1 is responsible for G and C transversions that predominate during base excision repair (inferred from mice in Jansen et al. 2006, Masuda et al. 2009), while POLH can create mutations at A and T residues (reviewed in Eckert 2023).<br>The error-prone polymerase leaves single-strand nick that is ligated by an unknown ligase that may be LIG1 or LIG3." ;
        <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label>
                "Error-rone base excision repair (BER) hypermutates immunoglobulin genes" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/contributor>
                "Edited: May, Bruce, 2025-10-12" , "Authored: May, Bruce, 2025-10-12" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Reviewed: Yu, Chuanjiang, 2026-04-27" ;
        <http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/date>
                "2026-07-02" ;
        <http://purl.org/pav/providedBy>
                "https://reactome.org" ;
        <http://www.geneontology.org/formats/oboInOwl#hasDbXref>
                "R-HSA-9968297" ;
